{"key":"post-12978696","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12978696</id>\n<content>With that much substrate, cooling is going to be the concern, not heating, especially once the bulk substrates begin to colonize.&amp;nbsp; That's enough to heat up a small bedroom to the point you'll need to keep a window open in winter, or run AC in summer to prevent overheating.&amp;nbsp; In addition, the CO2 level would be high enough to be dangerous to sleep in the same room.&amp;nbsp; Keep that in mind.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I keep around 1000 large filter patch bags colonizing in a room barely large enough to hold them all, and even with a window wide open in -30F temperatures, I use no supplemental heat to keep it between 65F-75F.&amp;nbsp; CO2 levels run about 12,000 ppm with that same window wide open too.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>12978744</next>\n<prev>12978691</prev>\n<first>12978524</first>\n<last>12979342</last>\n<when>1280544565</when>\n<utime>07/31/10 05:49 AM</utime>\n</post>"}